Grand Avenue\nWest Side\ni WISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nBILLIARDS\nEAST SIDE POOL HALL\nFrank Wkeelan, Prop.\nBilliards\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nBAKERIES\nH. A. HERSCHLEB\nBaker\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS. WISCONSIN\nGRAND RAPIDS BAKERY\nBakers\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nREAL ESTATE\nEOGOGER\u2019S EXCHANGE\nVine Street\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nB. G. EGGERT\nFarm Lands\nSecond Street South, Near Vine St.\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nBANKS\nWOOD COUNTY NATL. BANK\nCorner Vine and Second Sts.\nW ISCONSIN RAPIDS, W ISCONSIN\nlAT 010 YOU\nMAKE IN 1920?\nUNCLE SAM BEGINS COLLEC\nTION OF FEDERAL INCOME\nTAX FOR LAST YEAR.\nSame Rate As In 19*0\u2014Revenue Of\nficers to Visit Every County to\nAssist In Making Out\nthe Returns.\nWork has begmn on the collection\nof the income tax for the year 1920.\nUncle Sam, through the Bureau of\nInternal Revenue, is addressing to\nevery person in the United States the\nquestion, \u201cWhat was your net income\nfor 1920 The answer permits of no\nguesswork. Every single person\nwhose net income for 1920 was SI,OOO\nor more and every married person\nwhose net income was $2,000 or more\nis required to file a return under oath\nwith the collector of internal revenue\nfor the district in which he lives on\nor before March 15, 1921.\nThe penalty for failure is a fine of\nnot more than SI,OOO and an addi\ntional assessment of 25 per cent of\nthe amount of tax due. For willful\nrefusal to make a return the penalty\nis a fine of not more than SIO,OOO or j\nnot exceeding one year's imprison\nment, or both together with the costs\nof prosecution. A similar penalty is\nprovided for making a false or,\nfraudulent return, together with an j\nadditional assessment of 50 per cent j\nof the mount of tax evaded.\nW omen Must Pay Tax.\nThe income tax applies to women\nas well as men. Husband and wife\nmust consider the income of both plus\nthat of miner dependent children, and\nif the total equals or exceeds $2,000 a\nreturn must be filed. A minor who\nhas a net income in his own right of\nSI,OOO or more must file a separate\nreturn. To be allowed the $2,000 ex-\nemption a married person must be liv-\ning with husband or wife on the last\nday of the taxable year, December 31,\n1920. Divorcees, persons separated by\nmutual agreement, widows and wid\nowers, unless they are the sole sup\nport of others living in the same\nhousehold, in which case they are al\nlowed the $2,000 exemption granted\nthe head of a family, are entitled only\nto SI,OOO exemption.\nTax Rates For 1920.\nThe normal tax rale for 1920 is the\nsame as for 1919\u20144 per cent on the\nfirst $4,000 of net income above the\nexemption and 8 per cent on the re\nmaining net income. This applies to\nevery citizen and resident of the\nUnited States. In addition to the\nnormal tax a surtax is imposed upon\nnet income in excess of $5,000.\nInstructions on Form.\nFull instructions for making our re\nturns are contained on the forms, cop\nies of which may be obtained from\ncollectors of internal revenue. Per\nsons whose net income for 1920 was\n$5,000 or less should use Form 1040A.\nThose with incomes in excess of $5,\n000 should use Form 1040.\nRevenue officers will visit every\ncounty in the United States to assist\ntaxpayers in making out their re\nturns. The date of their arrival and\nl he location of their offices will be\nannounced by the press or may be\nascertained upon inquiry at the offices\nof collectors. This advisory service is\nwithout cost to taxpayers.\nCOAL DEALERS\nGOUGE PUBLIC\nOF MILLIONS\nTHE CHARGE\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014Coal con\nsumers of the United States have\nbeen mulcted of hundreds of millions\nof dollars and the health and welfare\nof th_- public jeopardized by the heart\nless orgy of coal profiteering, was\n\"harged in a report made to the sen\nate recently by Senator Calder of\nNew York and Kenyon of lowa, mem\nbers of a special Senate committee\ninvestigating the coal situation.\nSenator Calder. chairman, said he\nhad turned over to the Department of\njustice all the evidence collected with\na recommendation to promptly start\nprosecutions. The committee now is\ninvestigating the \u201cbuilding trust.\u201d\nCommenting upon newspaper re\nports of coal profiteering, Senator\nKenyon said evidence showed that\nmost of these reports failed to come\nwithin millions of dollars of the vast\nBANK OF GRAND RAPIDS\nGrand Avenue\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nCITIZENS NATIONAL BANK\nGrand Avenue\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nFIRST NATIONAL BANK\n(or. First and Second Streets North\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, W ISCONSIN\nj v-m? ,extorted. He scared the War\nDepartment for failing to protect it\nself frrm coal gougers by comman\ndeering coal as the Navy Department\ndid.\n$3,500,000 Profit Tax.\nI \u201cIn its report purchases,\u201d said the\nj ienator\u201e \u201cthe government paid an ex\ncess profit tax of $3,500,00, accord\ning to the testimony of expert coal\nmen before the committee. If the\nAmerican people have been robbed in\nthe same proportion, the excess prof\nits of coal dealers and operators run\nI into hundreds of millions.\nSenator Calder said he blamed the\nj government more than the coal deal\ners for the manner in which it per\nmitted itself to be robbed, and said\nsome government official should be\ncharged with sole responsibility of\npurchasing coal for the government.\n\u201cOnly One To Corrupt.\u201d\n\u201cThen,\u201d said Senator Borah, \u201cthe\ntask of the coal men would be easier.\nThey would have only one man to cor\nrupt.\u201d\nThe National Coal Association as\nserted today that \u201ca grievous injus\ntice\u201d had been done the Watkins Coal\nCompany of Pennsylvania in evidence\noffered yesterday that the company\nhad made a profit of $6 a ton on coal\nsold the War Department. Officials\nof the company, it was added, have\nasked for an opportunity to appear\nbefore the committee.\u2014Chicago Re\ncord-Herald Examiner.\nTHE SUGAR BOSH\nNOT EXTINCT\nOne of the \u201cold homesteads\u201d re\nported as having been in the same\nfamily for more than sixty years has\nupon it a tract of wood land including\na productive \u201csugar bush,\u201d from which\nthe family still make their yearly sup\nply of sugar, much as the original\npioneer owner did seventy years ago.\nMany of the early Wisconsin farms\nwere famous for their \u201csugar bush\u201d\nand in the manuscript census schedules\nof 1850, 1860 and 1870 it is common\nenough for farmers to list among their\nproducts a quantity of maple sugar.\nOne farm in Waukesha County for\nexample, listed in 1870 five hundred\npounds of it. It has been supposed\nthat sugar making had become a lost\nart, but the farm report alluded to\nsuggests that it probably persists in\nvarious places. The State Historical\nSociety would be glad to learn of\nother old homesteads having a sugar\nbush.\nTO HOLD STATE\nLEGION MEETING\nAT MARSHFIELD\nMARSHFIELD\u2014WiIIiam J. Lessel\nyong post Nc. 54, American Legion,\nat its annual business meeting elected\nthe following officers: D. A. Caldwell,\npost commander; Fred Braehm, vice\ncommander; Frank L. Normington,\nhistorian; Glenn V. Kraus, finance of\nficer; Charles M. Pors, cnapiain; Fred\nReeths, Jr., master-at-arms.\nLate in January the post will enter\ntain the commanders and adjutants\nof the 300 Wisconsin posts at the state\nmeeting. An invitation has been sene\nto Maj. Gen. Wood to be the principal\nspeaker. National Commander Gal\nbraith and Claudius G. Pendill of Ke\nnosha, state commander, will also be\non the program.\nTENTH ANNUAL\nROAD,'SCHOOL\nMADISON\u2014The Wisconsin High\nway Commission announces the Tenth\nAnnual Read School to be held in\nMusic Hail on the University Campus\nit Madison from January 31 to Febr\nuary 4 inclusive. \u201cIt is the purpose\u201d\nsays the announcement, \u201cto make this\nschool better and more helpful than\never before.\u201d Among the subjects\nupon which papers will be read and\ni cussion held are Patrol Mainten\nance, Administration, Construction,\nContractual Relations, County Organ\nization. Current Problems, Annual\nLegislation. The regular dinner will\nbe held on the evening of Thursday,\nFebruary 3. The Highway Commis\nsion advises all who contemplate at\ntending the school to make their i*es\nervations at once, as other conventions\nj will be held in Madison that week.\nDRUGGISTS\nSAM CHURCH\nCorner Third and Grand Avenues\nWhere Street Car Stops\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nDALY DRUG JEWELRY CO.\nOak and Second Streets\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS. WISCONSIN\nPROSPERITY\nJUST AHEAD\nThere is much comfort to be had\nfrom the statement recently of Judge\nElbert H. Gary, head of the United\nStates Steel corporation, the greatest\nbusiness concern the world has ever\nproduced.\nJudge Gary says a long period of\nwonderful prosperity is just ahead of\nthe people of the United States.\nW her. Judge Gary opens his mouth\nhe is in the habit of saying something\nand he never says a thing unless he\nknows what he is* talking about.\nHe has been a wise prophet in the\npast, because he possesse the ability\nto read conditions and possibilities as\nthey are.\nThere is no reason why his prophesy\nI should not be one of wisdom in this\ni case, because there is no reason why\ni we should not prosper and every rea\nson why we should.\nBanks and financiers generally state\ni that we have passed through our\nworst period of depression and are\nnow on the up grade. Only the rank\nest kind of pessimism can hold us\nback.\nAnd who wants to be a pessimist\nI when every human instinct spurns us\non to optimism\nLet\u2019s demonstrate our faith in the\nreturn of prosperity by recognizing\nthe fact that it is here and by doing\nour share toward its maintenance in\nthis community.\nLet the wacthword be production,\nwisdom in spending, and the employ\nment of a systematic course of sav\ning.\nA proportionate amount of the\nnrosperity of the country belongs to\nthe people of this community.\nLet\u2019s get all we can and keep all\nwe get.\nOther communities will be doing the\nsame.\nWATSON TO\nTOE RESCUE\nThomas E. Watson, the new United\nStates senator from Georgia, is to in\ntroduce a bill in the senate making\nliberty bonds legal tender. This\nwould put them on a par with the\nnational currency and restore them to\nat least par value.\nIf the government ever hopes to\nsell another bond in this country in\ntime of emergency it will do well to\nprotect the bondholders now.\nIt requires simply an act of con\ngress to make every one of these\nbonds legal tender. That would re\nquire every person to accept -them in\npayment of obligations just the sarr e\nas currency.\nThey would possess an added advan\ntage over currency in that they would\nbe drawing interest where currency\ndoes not.\nThey would becoine a possession of\nvalue even to the small invester,\nwhereas now they are but a despised\nand depreciating drug in the market.\nIt\u2019s clearly up to our Uncle Samuel,\nso shrewd in many things but so blind\nin this, for some of these days he may\nneed the wherewithal! to again patch\nhis pants.\nAnd the dear and confiding public\nhas a disagreeable habit of remem\nbering disagreeable things.\nDAIRYMEN\nAND MARKET\nCONDITIONS\nMADISON\u2014Wheat standard mid\ndlings are now being quoted at $2.00\nto $4.00 less per ton than wheat bran,\nalthough the former has a higher feed\ning value and usually sells at a hign\ner price, says Prof. W. H. Strowd in\ncharge of the Feed division of the\nState Department of Agriculture.\nWithin the present year middlings\nhave been SIO.OO to $15.00 higher than\nbran. Dairymen should take advan\ntage of the present market conditions\nby substituting middlings for bran in\ntheir dairy rations, Professor Strowd\nadvises. Even at equal prices mid\ndlings are preferable to bran but most\nfarmers, as a matter of habit, are\nstill baying bran when a more nutri\ntious feed may be had at a lower\nprice. By taking advantage of mar\nket changes farmers can affect a con\nsiderable saving in their feed bills.\nJOHNSON HILL CO.\nMain Floor\nI\nThird and Grand Avenues\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nF. L. STEIB\n104 First Street North\nOpposite First National Bank\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nWOOD COUNTY DRUG CO.\nE. M. Coyle. Prop.\nine Street Near Bridge\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS. WISCONSIN\nOTTO'S PHARMACY\nA. C. Otto, Prop.\nThe Rcxall Store\nGrand Avenue\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS. WISCONSIN\nELECTRICAL SUPPLIES\nHEPRICH SHERMAN\nGrand Avenue\nW est Side\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nSTAUB\u2019S ELECTRIC SHOP\n127 First Street North\nEast Side\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nJEWELERS\nLOUIS REICHEL\nVine Street\nEast Side\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, W ISCONSIN\nU. S. BRIGGSS\nGrand Avenue\nWest Side\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nMISCELLANEOUS\nCAREY CONCRETE CO.\nSeventeenth Avenue\nWest Side\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nMISS ANNA SCHULTZ\nBeauty Parlors\nWood County Realty Bldg.\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nSTEINBERG EPSTEIN\nHides and Furs\nGrand Avenue\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nFRANK GARBER\nIron and Metal Cos.\nChase Street\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nAUTO TRIM SHOP\nR. F. Sweet, Prop.\nOpposite Henke Grocery Company\nSecond Street North\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nNORMINGTON BROS.\nLaunderers\u2014Dry Cleaners\nFirst Avenue South, West Side\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nFLOUR MILLS\nGRAND RAPIDS MILLING CO.\nThird Avenue and\nRoosevelt Street\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nMcKERCHER ROSSIER\nCorner Eighth and\nGrand Avenue\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nFLORISTS\nEBSEN\u2019S GREEN HOUSE\n405-407 Saratoga Street\nEast Side\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nPHILLIP\u2019S FLOWER SHOP\nCorner Second and\nOak Streets\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nDR. W. C. WEIRICK\nChiropractor\nWood County Realty Cos, Building\nRoom 12.\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WISCONSIN\nJ. R. RAGAN\nLicensed Embalmer and Undertaker.\nPhones: House 69; Store 313;\nJohn Ernser, House Phone 435\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS. WISCONSIN\nORSON P. COCHRAN\nPiano Tuner\nBest work gua